******
[1] Illinois, McLean county
Date: Tue 6 Jun 2017
Source: The Pantagraph [edited]
http://www.pantagraph.com/news/local/testing-encouraged-amid-mumps-outbreak/article_cfcf971c-6b33-556a-ba8e-2d0d27fe36f1.html


A total of 5 McLean County residents have confirmed cases of mumps, leading the county health department on [Tue 6 Jun 2017] to encourage people experiencing symptoms to isolate from others until they can be tested for the virus.

None of the 5 residents -- ages 22 -- 52 -- needed to be hospitalized and all are recovering, said Lisa Slater of the McLean County Health Department. The agency is working with the infected individuals and notifying their close contacts about possible exposure to the virus.

"We need to protect our most vulnerable populations -- those who cannot get the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine because of age or illness -- from exposure to mumps virus," Melissa Graven, health department communicable disease supervisor, said in a statement for several days.

People experiencing symptoms should stay home and call their health care provider. Everyone else should make sure they are up to date with their MMR vaccinations and, if they aren't, to make vaccination a priority, the health department said.

[Byline: Paul Swiech]

