[3] New York, Capital region
Date: Thu 8 Jun 2017
Source: Times Union [edited]
http://www.timesunion.com/allwcm/article/Capital-Region-has-first-mumps-outbreak-in-years-11206309.php


If you feel like you might have a bad cold, don't shrug it off. Swollen jaw or not, it could be mumps.

The Capital Region [New York] is experiencing its 1st outbreak of mumps in years, with 45 cases in the 4-county region so far in 2017. For some parts of the area, these are the 1st cases of mumps in several years. And in Rensselaer County this year's 2 reported cases are the 1st seen there in 20 years, said Public Health Director Mary Fran Wachunas.

Albany County has seen the lion's share of mumps this year [2017], with 29 cases.
Most of them are traceable to 2 locations where the virus that causes the disease has spread. One is the University at Albany, where 22 patients had an association. The other is a local sports team, which had 6 cases.

Mumps cases by county, 2017

Albany : 29
Saratoga: 13
Rensselaer: 2
Schenectady: 1

In Saratoga County, where there have been 13 diagnosed cases of mumps, however, the patients are not connected by community, facility or demographic. That caused county officials to advise residents with suspected mumps symptoms to see a doctor immediately.

The most well-known symptom of mumps are swollen glands under the ears or jaw. But some patients who have the illness do not have that telltale sign, said Dr Rebecca Kobos, medical director for student health at UAlbany. Headache, muscle aches, loss of appetite and fever may be enough to indicate mumps, Kobos said, especially if a patient has been exposed to someone with the virus.

Her advice: See a doctor and take it seriously. Rest and stay away from work or school, so you don't expose other people to the illness. Rare but serious complications of mumps include swelling of the reproductive organs or the brain, as well as deafness.
Common sense is also handy.

"Precautions as simple as regular handwashing and covering one's mouth when coughing can go a long way to halt the spread of the virus," said Catherine Duncan, director of public health in Saratoga County.

[Byline: Claire Hughes]

